1
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:13,155
Hey everyone, where we last left off I

2
00:00:13,155 --> 00:00:15,475
showed what linear transformations look like and how

3
00:00:15,475 --> 00:00:17,315
to represent them using matrices.

4
00:00:18,115 --> 00:00:19,955
This is worth a quick recap because it's

5
00:00:19,955 --> 00:00:22,195
just really important, but of course if this

6
00:00:22,195 --> 00:00:23,955
feels like more than just a recap go

7
00:00:23,955 --> 00:00:25,075
back and watch the full video.

8
00:00:25,900 --> 00:00:29,660
Technically speaking, linear transformations are functions with vectors

9
00:00:29,660 --> 00:00:31,900
as inputs and vectors as outputs. But I

10
00:00:31,900 --> 00:00:33,340
showed last time how we can think about

11
00:00:33,340 --> 00:00:36,220
them visually as smooshing around space in such

12
00:00:36,220 --> 00:00:38,300
a way that grid lines stay parallel and

13
00:00:38,300 --> 00:00:40,805
evenly spaced, and so that the origin remains

14
00:00:40,805 --> 00:00:41,445
fixed.

15
00:00:41,765 --> 00:00:44,645
The key takeaway was that a linear transformation

16
00:00:44,645 --> 00:00:47,125
is completely determined by where it takes the

17
00:00:47,125 --> 00:00:49,285
basis vectors of the space, which for two

18
00:00:49,285 --> 00:00:51,365
dimensions means I hat and j hat.

19
00:00:52,070 --> 00:00:54,150
This is because any other vector could be

20
00:00:54,150 --> 00:00:56,150
described as a linear combination

21
00:00:56,150 --> 00:00:57,670
of those basis vectors.

22
00:00:57,830 --> 00:00:59,990
A vector with coordinates is

23
00:00:59,990 --> 00:01:02,230
x times I hat plus y times j

24
00:01:02,230 --> 00:01:02,710
hat.

25
00:01:03,510 --> 00:01:04,790
After going through the transformation,

26
00:01:05,115 --> 00:01:07,595
this property that grid lines remain parallel and

27
00:01:07,595 --> 00:01:10,155
evenly spaced has a wonderful consequence.

28
00:01:10,475 --> 00:01:12,315
The place where your vector lands will be

29
00:01:12,315 --> 00:01:14,875
x times the transformed version of I hat

30
00:01:14,875 --> 00:01:17,355
plus y times the transformed version of j

31
00:01:17,355 --> 00:01:17,595
hat.

32
00:01:18,250 --> 00:01:19,930
This means if you keep a record of

33
00:01:19,930 --> 00:01:22,330
the coordinates where I hat lands and the

34
00:01:22,330 --> 00:01:25,050
coordinates where j hat lands, you can compute

35
00:01:25,050 --> 00:01:27,290
that a vector which starts at x y

36
00:01:27,370 --> 00:01:29,690
must land on x times the new coordinates

37
00:01:29,690 --> 00:01:31,770
of I hat plus y times the new

38
00:01:31,770 --> 00:01:32,730
coordinates of j hat.

39
00:01:33,445 --> 00:01:35,605
The convention is to record the coordinates of

40
00:01:35,605 --> 00:01:37,445
where I hat and j hat land as

41
00:01:37,445 --> 00:01:39,125
the columns of a matrix

42
00:01:39,285 --> 00:01:41,205
and to define this sum of the scaled

43
00:01:41,205 --> 00:01:43,445
versions of those columns by x and y

44
00:01:43,445 --> 00:01:45,365
to be matrix vector multiplication.

45
00:01:46,100 --> 00:01:48,740
In this way, a matrix represents a specific

46
00:01:48,740 --> 00:01:51,780
linear transformation and multiplying a matrix by a

47
00:01:51,780 --> 00:01:54,420
vector is what it means computationally

48
00:01:54,420 --> 00:01:56,180
to apply that transformation

49
00:01:56,180 --> 00:01:57,060
to that vector.

50
00:01:58,595 --> 00:02:01,235
Alright. Recap over. On to the new stuff.

51
00:02:01,555 --> 00:02:04,195
Oftentimes, you find yourself wanting to describe the

52
00:02:04,195 --> 00:02:06,195
effects of applying one transformation

53
00:02:06,195 --> 00:02:07,315
and then another.

54
00:02:07,635 --> 00:02:09,955
For example, maybe you wanna describe what happens

55
00:02:09,955 --> 00:02:12,035
when you first rotate the plane 90 degrees

56
00:02:12,035 --> 00:02:13,155
counterclockwise

57
00:02:13,130 --> 00:02:14,810
then apply a shear.

58
00:02:15,370 --> 00:02:17,770
The overall effect here from start to finish

59
00:02:17,770 --> 00:02:19,850
is another linear transformation

60
00:02:19,850 --> 00:02:22,090
distinct from the rotation and the shear.

61
00:02:22,410 --> 00:02:25,050
This new linear transformation is commonly called the

62
00:02:25,050 --> 00:02:25,930
composition

63
00:02:25,930 --> 00:02:28,250
of the two separate transformations we applied.

64
00:02:28,795 --> 00:02:30,795
And like any linear transformation,

65
00:02:30,875 --> 00:02:32,795
it can be described with a matrix all

66
00:02:32,795 --> 00:02:35,035
of its own by following I hat and

67
00:02:35,035 --> 00:02:35,835
j hat.

68
00:02:36,155 --> 00:02:37,195
In this example,

69
00:02:37,355 --> 00:02:39,595
the ultimate landing spot for I hat after

70
00:02:39,595 --> 00:02:40,795
both transformations

71
00:02:40,875 --> 00:02:43,070
is one one. So let's make that the

72
00:02:43,070 --> 00:02:44,510
first column of a matrix.

73
00:02:44,910 --> 00:02:47,550
Likewise, j hat ultimately ends up at the

74
00:02:47,550 --> 00:02:50,350
location negative one zero, so we make that

75
00:02:50,350 --> 00:02:52,190
the second column of the matrix.

76
00:02:52,590 --> 00:02:55,790
This new matrix captures the overall effect of

77
00:02:55,790 --> 00:02:58,535
applying a rotation then a shear, but as

78
00:02:58,535 --> 00:03:01,655
one single action rather than two successive ones.

79
00:03:03,175 --> 00:03:04,615
Here's one way to think about that new

80
00:03:04,615 --> 00:03:06,695
matrix. If you were to take some vector

81
00:03:06,695 --> 00:03:08,855
and pump it through the rotation then the

82
00:03:08,855 --> 00:03:09,495
shear,

83
00:03:09,735 --> 00:03:11,255
the long way to compute where it ends

84
00:03:11,255 --> 00:03:13,330
up is to first multiply it on the

85
00:03:13,330 --> 00:03:15,170
left by the rotation matrix,

86
00:03:15,490 --> 00:03:17,970
then take whatever you get and multiply that

87
00:03:17,970 --> 00:03:20,130
on the left by the shear matrix.

88
00:03:20,370 --> 00:03:23,170
This is numerically speaking what it means to

89
00:03:23,170 --> 00:03:25,490
apply a rotation then a shear to a

90
00:03:25,490 --> 00:03:26,050
given vector.

91
00:03:26,725 --> 00:03:28,405
But whatever you get should be the same

92
00:03:28,405 --> 00:03:30,965
as just applying this new composition matrix that

93
00:03:30,965 --> 00:03:33,045
we just found by that same vector,

94
00:03:33,285 --> 00:03:35,445
no matter what vector you chose. Since this

95
00:03:35,445 --> 00:03:37,685
new matrix is supposed to capture the same

96
00:03:37,685 --> 00:03:40,885
overall effect as the rotation then shear action.

97
00:03:42,450 --> 00:03:44,370
Based on how things are written down here,

98
00:03:44,450 --> 00:03:46,130
I think it's reasonable to call this new

99
00:03:46,130 --> 00:03:48,930
matrix the product of the original two matrices.

100
00:03:48,930 --> 00:03:49,730
Don't you?

101
00:03:50,370 --> 00:03:51,970
We can think about how to compute that

102
00:03:51,970 --> 00:03:54,210
product more generally in just a moment, but

103
00:03:54,210 --> 00:03:55,810
it's way too easy to get lost in

104
00:03:55,810 --> 00:03:58,815
the forest of numbers. Always remember that multiplying

105
00:03:58,815 --> 00:04:01,615
two matrices like this has the geometric meaning

106
00:04:01,615 --> 00:04:03,535
of applying one transformation

107
00:04:03,535 --> 00:04:04,575
then another.

108
00:04:06,095 --> 00:04:07,935
One thing that's kinda weird here is that

109
00:04:07,935 --> 00:04:09,615
this has us reading from right to left.

110
00:04:09,870 --> 00:04:12,430
You first apply the transformation represented by the

111
00:04:12,430 --> 00:04:14,430
matrix on the right, then you apply the

112
00:04:14,430 --> 00:04:16,990
transformation represented by the matrix on the left.

113
00:04:17,310 --> 00:04:20,110
This stems from function notation since we write

114
00:04:20,110 --> 00:04:22,270
functions on the left of variables. So every

115
00:04:22,270 --> 00:04:24,350
time you compose two functions, you always have

116
00:04:24,350 --> 00:04:26,495
to read it right to left. Good news

117
00:04:26,495 --> 00:04:28,415
for the Hebrew readers, bad news for the

118
00:04:28,415 --> 00:04:29,135
rest of us.

119
00:04:29,775 --> 00:04:31,375
Let's look at another example.

120
00:04:31,615 --> 00:04:34,015
Take the matrix with columns one one and

121
00:04:34,015 --> 00:04:37,135
negative two zero whose transformation looks like this,

122
00:04:37,935 --> 00:04:39,135
and let's call it m one.

123
00:04:40,100 --> 00:04:42,820
Next, take the matrix with columns zero one

124
00:04:42,820 --> 00:04:45,860
and two zero whose transformation looks like this

125
00:04:47,540 --> 00:04:49,620
and let's call that guy m two.

126
00:04:49,940 --> 00:04:52,340
The total effect of applying m one then

127
00:04:52,340 --> 00:04:54,500
m two gives us a new transformation.

128
00:04:54,580 --> 00:04:55,965
So let's find its matrix.

129
00:04:56,205 --> 00:04:57,885
But this time, let's see if we can

130
00:04:57,885 --> 00:05:00,125
do it without watching the animations

131
00:05:00,125 --> 00:05:03,245
and instead just using the numerical entries in

132
00:05:03,245 --> 00:05:04,125
each matrix.

133
00:05:04,765 --> 00:05:06,525
First, we need to figure out where I

134
00:05:06,525 --> 00:05:07,165
hat goes.

135
00:05:07,860 --> 00:05:10,660
After applying m one, the new coordinates of

136
00:05:10,660 --> 00:05:12,260
I hat by definition

137
00:05:12,340 --> 00:05:14,420
are given by that first column of m

138
00:05:14,420 --> 00:05:16,340
one, namely one one.

139
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:19,300
To see what happens after applying m two,

140
00:05:19,540 --> 00:05:22,340
multiply the matrix for m two by that

141
00:05:22,340 --> 00:05:23,460
vector one one.

142
00:05:25,515 --> 00:05:27,195
Working it out the way that I described

143
00:05:27,195 --> 00:05:30,235
last video, you'll get the vector two one.

144
00:05:30,635 --> 00:05:32,155
This will be the first column of the

145
00:05:32,155 --> 00:05:33,435
composition matrix.

146
00:05:34,395 --> 00:05:37,100
Likewise, to follow j hat, the second column

147
00:05:37,100 --> 00:05:38,940
of m one tells us that it first

148
00:05:38,940 --> 00:05:40,860
lands on negative two zero.

149
00:05:42,940 --> 00:05:45,260
Then when we apply m two to that

150
00:05:45,260 --> 00:05:45,980
vector,

151
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:50,060
you can work out the matrix vector product

152
00:05:50,060 --> 00:05:51,820
to get zero negative two,

153
00:05:52,485 --> 00:05:54,725
which becomes the second column of our composition

154
00:05:54,725 --> 00:05:55,525
matrix.

155
00:05:56,805 --> 00:05:58,885
Let me talk through that same process again,

156
00:05:58,885 --> 00:06:01,365
but this time I'll show variable entries in

157
00:06:01,365 --> 00:06:03,125
each matrix just to show that the same

158
00:06:03,125 --> 00:06:05,045
line of reasoning works for any matrices.

159
00:06:05,400 --> 00:06:07,400
This is more symbol heavy and will require

160
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:09,080
some more room, but it should be pretty

161
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:11,320
satisfying for anyone who has previously been taught

162
00:06:11,320 --> 00:06:13,960
matrix multiplication the more rote way.

163
00:06:14,440 --> 00:06:16,600
To follow where I hat goes, start by

164
00:06:16,600 --> 00:06:18,360
looking at the first column of the matrix

165
00:06:18,360 --> 00:06:19,965
on the right since this is where I

166
00:06:19,965 --> 00:06:21,325
hat initially lands.

167
00:06:21,885 --> 00:06:24,365
Multiplying that column by the matrix on the

168
00:06:24,365 --> 00:06:26,285
left is how you can tell where the

169
00:06:26,285 --> 00:06:28,845
intermediate version of I hat ends up after

170
00:06:28,845 --> 00:06:30,285
applying the second transformation.

171
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:33,980
So the first column of the composition matrix

172
00:06:33,980 --> 00:06:36,540
will always equal the left matrix times the

173
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:38,300
first column of the right matrix.

174
00:06:42,300 --> 00:06:42,860
Likewise,

175
00:06:43,275 --> 00:06:45,675
j hat will always initially land on the

176
00:06:45,675 --> 00:06:47,435
second column of the right matrix.

177
00:06:48,795 --> 00:06:51,515
So multiplying the left matrix by this second

178
00:06:51,515 --> 00:06:54,475
column will give its final location and hence

179
00:06:54,475 --> 00:06:57,035
that's the second column of the composition matrix.

180
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:02,640
Notice, there's a lot of symbols here and

181
00:07:02,640 --> 00:07:04,320
it's common to be taught this formula as

182
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:07,200
something to memorize along with a certain algorithmic

183
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:09,440
process to kind of help remember it. But

184
00:07:09,440 --> 00:07:11,440
I really do think that before memorizing that

185
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:13,345
process you should get in the habit of

186
00:07:13,345 --> 00:07:16,625
thinking about what matrix multiplication really represents,

187
00:07:16,785 --> 00:07:19,185
applying one transformation after another.

188
00:07:19,665 --> 00:07:21,345
Trust me, this will give you a much

189
00:07:21,345 --> 00:07:23,825
better conceptual framework that makes the properties of

190
00:07:23,825 --> 00:07:25,025
matrix multiplication

191
00:07:25,025 --> 00:07:26,225
much easier to understand.

192
00:07:26,960 --> 00:07:29,600
For example, here's a question. Does it matter

193
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:31,600
what order we put the two matrices in

194
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:33,040
when we multiply them?

195
00:07:33,840 --> 00:07:36,240
Well, let's think through a simple example like

196
00:07:36,240 --> 00:07:37,360
the one from earlier.

197
00:07:37,520 --> 00:07:39,600
Take a shear which fixes I hat and

198
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:41,565
smooshes j hat over to the right and

199
00:07:41,565 --> 00:07:43,085
a 90 degree rotation.

200
00:07:43,565 --> 00:07:46,285
If you first do the shear then rotate,

201
00:07:46,445 --> 00:07:47,965
we can see that I hat ends up

202
00:07:47,965 --> 00:07:49,965
at zero one and j hat ends up

203
00:07:49,965 --> 00:07:52,525
at negative one one, both are generally pointing

204
00:07:52,525 --> 00:07:53,405
close together.

205
00:07:53,885 --> 00:07:56,365
If you first rotate then do the shear,

206
00:07:57,880 --> 00:07:59,880
I hat ends up over at one one

207
00:07:59,880 --> 00:08:02,200
and j hat is often a different direction

208
00:08:02,200 --> 00:08:04,680
at negative one zero and they're pointing, you

209
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:05,880
know, farther apart.

210
00:08:06,280 --> 00:08:08,760
The overall effect here is clearly different. So

211
00:08:08,760 --> 00:08:10,680
evidently order totally does matter.

212
00:08:12,125 --> 00:08:14,845
Notice, by thinking in terms of transformations,

213
00:08:14,925 --> 00:08:16,125
that's the kind of thing that you can

214
00:08:16,125 --> 00:08:18,125
do in your head by visualizing.

215
00:08:18,125 --> 00:08:20,205
No matrix multiplication necessary.

216
00:08:21,645 --> 00:08:23,805
I remember when I first took linear algebra,

217
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:26,060
there was this one homework problem that asked

218
00:08:26,060 --> 00:08:28,060
us to prove that matrix multiplication

219
00:08:28,060 --> 00:08:29,500
is associative.

220
00:08:29,660 --> 00:08:31,660
This means that if you have three matrices,

221
00:08:31,660 --> 00:08:33,660
a, b, and c, and you multiply them

222
00:08:33,660 --> 00:08:35,980
all together, it shouldn't matter if you first

223
00:08:35,980 --> 00:08:38,860
compute a times b, then multiply the result

224
00:08:38,860 --> 00:08:40,995
by c, or if you first multiply b

225
00:08:40,995 --> 00:08:43,715
times c, then multiply that result by a

226
00:08:43,715 --> 00:08:46,035
on the left. In other words, it doesn't

227
00:08:46,035 --> 00:08:47,875
matter where you put the parentheses.

228
00:08:48,275 --> 00:08:49,955
Now, if you try to work through this

229
00:08:49,955 --> 00:08:53,130
numerically like I did back then, it's horrible,

230
00:08:53,130 --> 00:08:56,410
just horrible, and unenlightening for that matter. But

231
00:08:56,410 --> 00:08:59,130
when you think about matrix multiplication as applying

232
00:08:59,130 --> 00:09:01,050
one transformation after another,

233
00:09:01,370 --> 00:09:03,130
this property is just trivial.

234
00:09:03,290 --> 00:09:04,010
Can you see why?

235
00:09:04,845 --> 00:09:06,605
What it's saying is that if you first

236
00:09:06,605 --> 00:09:09,805
apply c then b then a, it's the

237
00:09:09,805 --> 00:09:12,765
same as applying c then b then a.

238
00:09:13,005 --> 00:09:14,925
I mean, there's nothing to prove. You're just

239
00:09:14,925 --> 00:09:17,245
applying the same three things one after the

240
00:09:17,245 --> 00:09:18,685
other, all in the same order.

241
00:09:19,490 --> 00:09:21,890
This might feel like cheating, but it's not.

242
00:09:21,970 --> 00:09:23,810
This is an honest to goodness proof that

243
00:09:23,810 --> 00:09:26,210
matrix multiplication is associative.

244
00:09:26,290 --> 00:09:28,130
And even better than that, it's a good

245
00:09:28,130 --> 00:09:30,610
explanation for why that property should be true.

246
00:09:31,665 --> 00:09:33,505
I really do encourage you to play around

247
00:09:33,505 --> 00:09:36,705
more with this idea, imagining two different transformations,

248
00:09:36,785 --> 00:09:38,865
thinking about what happens when you apply one

249
00:09:38,865 --> 00:09:40,705
after the other, and then working out the

250
00:09:40,705 --> 00:09:42,385
matrix product numerically.

251
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:44,465
Trust me, this is the kind of playtime

252
00:09:44,465 --> 00:09:46,385
that really makes the idea sink in.

253
00:09:47,150 --> 00:09:48,990
In the next video, I'll start talking about

254
00:09:48,990 --> 00:09:52,110
extending these ideas beyond just two dimensions. See

255
00:09:52,110 --> 00:09:52,430
you then.
